article.description: Cheryl Ford scored 14 points and rookie Tasha Humphrey added 12 to keep the Detroit Shock unbeaten at home with a 66-63 victory Wednesday over the Chicago Sky.
article.headline: Ford, Humphrey help Detroit hold off Chicago
article.linkText: Shock edge Sky to remain unbeaten at home
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Detroit Shock know that no lead is safe, even at home.

Four days after blowing an 18-point lead in a loss at New York, the Shock were up by as many as 23 before letting Chicago get back into the game on Wednesday.

But Detroit hung on for a 66-63 victory after the Sky missed four game-tying 3-point attempts in the final minute.

"In New York, it was a lot about running out of gas," Shock coach Bill Laimbeer said, "but today, we just got selfish. We were taking shots with an 18-point lead that we should never have taken."

Cheryl Ford had 14 points to help Detroit maintain the league's only unbeaten home record (10-0), but she's concerned about Detroit's propensity to lose big leads.

"We did it again," Ford said. "We have to learn how to keep our focus and build on leads. We got a W today, and that's the important thing, but it was too tough."

Ford and rookie Tasha Humphrey, who scored 12 points, were the only Shock players to reach double figures. Guards Katie Smith and Deanna Nolan combined for just 12 points on 5-for-17 shooting, while top reserve Plenette Pierson had nine.

In front of 15,210 fans that included mostly kids from summer camps, the Shock led 39-22 at halftime before Chicago outscored them 41-27 in the second half.

"My team showed up in the second half, but unfortunately, one half of a basketball game against the conference-leading team isn't going to be good enough to win," said Chicago coach Steven Key.

Jia Perkins of the Sky led all scorers with 26 points, and Candice Dupree had 12.

"They came out ready to play, because they knew we beat them the last time at our place," Dupree said. "The first half for us was sloppy, but we came out with a lot more energy in the second half."

The Sky trailed by as many as 23 in the first half, but put together a rally in the fourth, pulling within 53-47 on Quianna Chaney's layup with 6:11 left.

After Humphrey split a pair of free throws, Perkins made it 54-50 with a 3-pointer, then added a pair of free throws to draw Chicago within two midway through the quarter.

Perkins and Brooke Wyckoff missed game-tying 3-pointers in the final 45 seconds, but Price's put-back made it 64-63 with 38 seconds to go.

Alexis Hornbuckle tapped in an offensive rebound to move the margin back to three, and Perkins missed twice in the final seconds.
